Governor,

One of the great unheard of costs in the mortgage foreclosure problem is the uncontrolled and unregulated legal fees imposed on homeowners in North Carolina during a foreclosure process. While it may be possible for a homeowner to work at catching up on their regular mortgage payments, they will often get hit with massive legal fees.

In fact, the legal fees charged during a NC foreclosure process don't even truly match up with the NC Attorney's Code of Conduct, which basically states that fees be reasonable and relate to the experience of people doing the work, i.e. if a legal secretary prepares a filing, don't charge full attorney legal fees.

I know from first-hand experience how onerous and unfair these fees can be. I went through a foreclosure on a property i owned in Charlotte. Due to various circumstances beyond my immediate control I fell behind on the payments. I was actually able to come up with all the payments and legal fees due two days before the foreclosure date. I called the mortgage company to tell them I had the funds, when  they told me there was now "another $2000 in fees to pay". obviously I was unable to come up with that additional amount in two days and lost the property.

I called the mortgage company and asked for a breakdown of the fees being charged for the foreclosure - remember I am being billed these. They told me that they could not provide them and i would need to call the attorney;'s office directly and ask them. After numerous attempts to track down exactly who at the Attorney's office I needed to call, I asked them directly for a breakdown of the fees being charged. The response was that was between  them and the mortgage company and I needed to ask the mortgage company.

Hah!

Isn't it amazing that the people being billed for legal fees that may cause them to lose their home are not provided with any details as to what those fees are. Just a total amount that must be paid - or else. If you, as Governor, don't want to require reasanable limits on those fees, ast least it would be fair to require the mortgagors to provide a detailed bill of what they are charging for! Isn't that a reasonable request?

What's really amazing is that the state of North Carolina doesn't care.

South Carolina mandates a maximum amount on the fees that can be charged as part of a foreclosure proceeding. The amount is reasonable.

Why doesn't North Carolina?

If you want to do something to really help North Carolina homeowners suffering through a foreclosure proceeding, you will investigate this.
I look forward to your reply.

Sincerely,
Martin Bartlett.

