RE.: Prison Closure Proposals


Dear Governor Bev Perdue,

        Almost 27 years ago I left Germany and arrived here in the United States of America with my most priced possessions packed in to one suitcase and I have lived in North Carolina ever since.  I am a single mother of two beautiful children, which attend UNC Charlotte and Methodist University.  My life has not been easy and I lost my first born to SIDS almost 28 years ago. I had to work hard for what I have now and I also had to struggle to be able to hold on to it.  My husband abandoned us in 2005 after 18 years of marriage without a plausible reason and he made sure to clean out the bank accounts and take all the kids college money as well.  I raised my son and daughter to be law abiding citizens and to study hard to be able to make something out of their lives and to contribute to society by helping others.  I attended Fayetteville Technical Community College and by the end of 2005 I had earned two associates, one in Paralegal Technology and one in General Education but since my husband abandoned us and left us penniless I had to take the first job that was available to have some income coming into my household and  I started working for the Department of Correction, McCain Correctional Hospital, as of April 16, 2006.  I first worked as Medical Records Assistant III and I moved up to Office Assistant IV within one year. I work hard everyday and in the 21 months in my new position I have covered my old position for more than 8 months for various reasons and I have also trained two new employees in this position as well  and without ever getting any additional compensation. I believe in teamwork and I am a team player and a hard worker that helps anyone in need of assistance and to keep the workflow going to accomplish the departments day-to-day operations and mission of the department.  All in all, I take pride in all the work that I do because what I do
does not only reflect on the people and the department I work for but it also reflects on me.  I know I have much more potential than to work for the NC DOC but it is not easy to find a good job in North Carolina without having certain connections that others seem to have. 

        Now we are slated to be closed and morale at McCain is very low.  Most workers here are minorities, women, people of different national origin, most are older than forty, and we have many single parents as well.   The other facts are that most employees here only have a High School Diploma and some do not even have that and the income of DOC employees is the lowest pay of all State Departments and most have to work second jobs to be able to make ends meet.  All of us are devastated and scared and there is a great fear that we will not be placed in other state positions and that therefore our children will suffer.  The fear of being unemployed and of losing our homes and not being able to take care of our children is more than we can bare.  We do not understand why we are being slated to close while monies are being paid to six figure positions on the top of the hill and other monies are being made available for, Goodyear incentives, probation, community college staff and faculty raises, and teacher ABC raises while we will be losing our lively hood.  The Federal Stimulus Package is, and was, supposed to save and/or create 105,000 jobs, and not to shift money around by eliminating positions to create new ones for people with degrees.  As aforementioned, most employees at the NC DOC do not have any degrees beyond high school and therefore will be disadvantaged and not qualified to apply for the newly created positions.  DOC employees are the lowest paid State Employees and the least appreciated ones and we have been overlooked by our government and the General Assembly for years.  As comparison take a look at the  Office Assistant IV pay at DOC that never even reaches the median of the pay scale, even for employees that have worked for DOC for more than 20 years, whereas an Office Assistant IV at the Department of Crime Control and Public Safety makes the max salary to the last dollar of the maximum range available, even for new employees. Where is the equity and fairness in that?  To work in a prison is dangerous and stressful and employees have to be aware of their surroundings at all times.  As said before, we feel singled out and we feel unappreciated and we feel as the sacrificial lamb, not due to the budget shortfall but to shift money around from the jobs we will loose to some other newly created positions for probation and so that other state employees in the educational fields can receive raises.  How can that possibly save any money?  How will State Government attract good employees in the future when the ones it has, and that are faithfully serving, are being tossed to the side when the going gets tough, and are ignored when the going is good?

        We know that you have to make many difficult decisions but we would like to know what will happen to us, the Department of Correction employees, that will be laid off when you will close McCain Correctional Hospital and all the other employees of the smaller prisons that are on the Closure Proposal List?  We feel that the Reduction in Force letter that we will receive will be just a piece of paper that is of no value.  We are wondering why you are creating all these new jobs that most people that will be laid off will not be able to obtain because they do not have the education to qualify for these positions?  Could we possibly be trained and be sent to college by the state to be able to apply and to be able to feed our children and keep our homes or will we end up on the welfare list and in homeless shelters?  Most DOC employees live from paycheck to paycheck and have no savings.  So please think of all the families and especially the children you will be affecting with your decisions.  My children would have to drop out of college if I loose my job and therefore all the things you are trying to do for education will not be of any help to them and I am quite sure that the same would apply to many other children of DOC employees that you are planning to cut.  What is education made available going to do good when you have no time to be able to get educated because you cannot afford it because you have no time and have to work two jobs just to get by?  I, for my part, would love to go back to college to work toward my bachelors degree but I can not because I do not make enough money to put my two children and myself through college at the same time.  You see, my children are all I have and they come first, for they and their future are my main priority, but when I loose my job I can not even take care of their future anymore.  Please think about how you will affect all these children by laying us off, since children and education seem to be your main priority such should include the children of DOC employees and their future as well.   

