Subject: Guilford Correctional closing





Prisons are an unfortunate but necessary part of our landscape as a
society. 
I will admit upfront, to be one who sees them much more as a beginning
than 
an end.  I have volunteered in the NC prison system since 1992; first at

Sandy Ridge Correctional, then at Guilford Correctional since 1998 when 
Sandy Ridge closed, and in Central Prison with the Kairos ministry since

2000.  As anyone connected with prisons will tell you, the issue between

those who believe in compassion and forgiveness, versus those who want
to 
lock up criminals and throw away the key, is the purpose of prisons, not
how 
they work best.



It's really quite practical.  If inmates, through programs, and personal

interaction with volunteers, can begin to find moral grounding,
recognize 
their self-worth and purpose, and can seek opportunities to obtain and
keep 
a job, some pretty positive outcomes can occur.  First of all, they will

discover that 'citizens' are not the enemy, and some people actually
care 
about them.  Further, they will hunger to reenter society for 'good',
they 
will pay taxes, rather than consuming them, and the rate of recidivism
will 
decline.



For many years, Guilford Correction Institution, under the direction of 
Superintendent James Lacewell, has been a prison where their program 
enriches society, rather than just a place to hide our society's dirty 
secrets.  Numerous work release sponsors support the population,
resulting 
in men who are able to help support their families and/or pay the
financial 
debt of their sentence.  In addition, those on work release pay for
their 
own transportation and for room and board each month.  Finally, assuring

this system, more volunteer hours spent at Guilford Correctional than at
any 
other institution in the state.  It is the type of prison that our other

prisons should be.  Oak Ridge UMC is represented at Yokefellows,
Wednesday 
night services, and with the Community Volunteer program.



In 2001, there was an attempt to close Guilford Correctional; through
the 
efforts of many, it was saved and Alamance Correctional was closed.  In
the 
last 10-15 years, NC has closed ~35-40 prisons, each time further 
compressing the overcrowding.  It has again been proposed that Guilford
be 
closed, this time by the State (not DOC).  From the standpoint of our 
state's attempts at rehabilitation this is a very bad idea, but also,
what 
camp really has room for another 120 inmates?  What about our future as
a 
state?



I ask that you strongly support this institution.  Examine all the facts
and 
see if closing Guilford makes sense at any level.  I realize, like 
landfills, many people like to have prisons out of sight, but criminals
are 
products of the city, and city prisons are an opportunity for churches
and 
other volunteers to improve the quality of life right where they live,
and 
have the resources close at hand to do it.  Clearly the economy is
stressed, 
but don't punish a program that is contributing to the recovery, by
cramming 
its men into a situation where they will be surely be a drain on us,
from 
now until their death.  Thank you for your support of this very
important 
issue for Greensboro and our area.



Sincerely, Dan Nelson

