Along with the need to continue helping employees improve skills in basic literacy, computer literacy and other workplace skills, UNC also needs to look for opportunities to serve the larger population of North Carolina citizens.



Presently, UNC Facilities Services maintains more than 16 million square feet of facilities. The vast majority of these buildings use pneumatic technology to control heating, cooling and ventilation. The HVAC and control staff who maintain this equipment are skilled and knowledgeable at maintaining this older equipment, but are still learning to maintain the digital equipment installed in new facilities. The challenge of maintaining the mechanical systems while trying to master the new digital systems is a significant institutional challenge. The controls staff is also aging out of the system, and Building Services is not attracting new staff that can maintain both old (pneumatic) and new (digital) control technologies.



Wake Technical Institute offers an Associate of Arts degree in Air Conditioning, Heating, and Refrigeration Technology. This two-year degree includes coursework in digital controls as well as hydronic heating (steam) and chiller systems.



We propose that UNC establish a cooperative program with Wake Technical Institute as a means of attracting skilled staff to Building Services and Energy Services and supporting the state economy by providing a rich, learning environment for new workers. Not only can UNC provide the cooperative students with the opportunity to meet their degree requirements, but we will also provide graduates with employment and further training that will allow them to meet the requirements for licensing. This cooperative program would also create an opportunity for UNC's skilled staff to stay active and engaged after they retire by teaching and/or mentoring younger workers. And by increasing our digital controls staffing, we may also improve our opportunities to save energy.



